5 NEW SECTION. Section 2. Duties of interdisciplinary network of guardianship stakeholders.
6 The working interdisciplinary network of guardianship stakeholders shall:
7 (1) identify strengths and weaknesses in the state's current system of adult guardianship and
8 conservatorship;
9 (2) identify less restrictive decisionmaking options for incapacitated persons;
10 (3) review national standards on guardianship and conservatorship practices and recommend
11 standards for adoption in Montana;
12 (4) propose methods of training guardians and conservators in best practices or adopted
13 standards;
14 (5) recommend or conduct other outreach, education, and training as needed;
15 (6) make recommendations to the supreme court administrator regarding grants to be awarded as
16 provided in [section 3]; and
17 (7) serve as an ongoing problem-solving mechanism to enhance the quality of care and quality of
18 life for adults who are or may soon be in the guardianship or conservatorship system.
19
20 NEW SECTION. Section 3. Grants for public guardianship programs. (1) The judicial branch shall
21 make grants to organizations that provide guardianship services to indigent individuals for whom a guardian is
22 not otherwise available. The grants must be used to provide training and guidance to family members serving
23 as guardians, to public defenders and district court judges who are handling guardianship cases, and to
24 volunteer guardians of indigent individuals who are unable to pay for guardianship services.
25 (2) In making grants, the judicial branch shall consider:
26 (a) recommendations of the working interdisciplinary network of guardianship stakeholders
27 provided for in [section 2]; and
28 (b) geographic balance if awarding grants to more than one organization.
